# System overview
The system uses a master–slave architecture. Each instance can operate as either master or elevator. The master runs a TCP server and broadcasts its availability using UDP. Elevators on the network listen for these UDP broadcasts in order to discover the master and establish a TCP connection. Once connected, elevators communicate with the master through the TCP connection. They send updates such as button presses, floor changes, and obstruction status. This communication allows the master to maintain a global overview of all elevators and requests in the system.

When connected, the elevator simply executes the orders assigned by the master. Elevators are also capable of performing cab calls locally when they are not connected to the master. To prevent request loss, when an elevator detects a button press it immediately sends the request to the master while also storing it locally. The request is placed in a pending list until an acknowledgement is received. At the same time, the pending list is written to a file so it can survive restarts or failures. If the acknowledgement from the master is not received within a specified time limit, the elevator will resend the request.

The master is responsible for receiving button press events from elevators and assigning them to the most appropriate elevator. In addition to distributing orders, the master also controls the button lights for each elevator. This ensures that once a request has been received, the corresponding lights are updated to notify the user. The master also selects one elevator to act as a successor. The successor maintains a backup of the master's request queues so that it can take over if the master crashes or loses network connectivity.

When the master receives a request from an elevator, it adds the request to its queue and sends an updated backup to the successor. Only after the successor acknowledges that the backup has been received does the master distribute the order and send an acknowledgement back to the requesting elevator. If the current master fails due to a crash or network loss, the successor takes over the role of master. If the successor later disconnects, the current master will select a new successor among the remaining connected elevators.

If an elevator with active requests disconnects from the master, its hall calls are redistributed among the remaining connected elevators. Cab calls, however, remain associated with the original elevator. These cab calls are stored and resent to that elevator once it reconnects to the system.

# Running the Program
go run main.go -id=<elevator_id> [-successor]

## Flags
- **-id** (required)

    Sets the unique ID of the elevator instance.
- **-successor** (optional)

    If this flag is included, the elevator will start as the successor node. This allows it to take over as the master.

## Examples
- Start an elevator with ID pop:

    go run main.go -id=pop
- Start an elevator with ID pop and enable successor mode:

    go run main.go -id=pop -successor

